<span id="freeTextContainer3775557030589036628">My daughter read this book in school and went on and on about it for weeks. And, like a good mother, I responded with, &quot;uh huh, that&apos;s nice dear&quot; while really thinking about other things.<br/><br/>Then I bought her a copy and decided to read it myself. It hit me like a ton of bricks. I couldn&apos;t believe my daughter liked it so much because she is an insane animal lover. Her whole world revolves around knowing and preserving every animal species alive today.<br/><br/>But this is a good story, and probably more realis</span>
  <span id="freeText3775557030589036628" style="display:none">My daughter read this book in school and went on and on about it for weeks. And, like a good mother, I responded with, "uh huh, that's nice dear" while really thinking about other things.<br /><br />Then I bought her a copy and decided to read it myself. It hit me like a ton of bricks. I couldn't believe my daughter liked it so much because she is an insane animal lover. Her whole world revolves around knowing and preserving every animal species alive today.<br /><br />But this is a good story, and probably more realistic than we'd like to admit (well, except for the plotting alligator). It was powerfully sad, and although I loved it, it will be awhile before I have the emotional stamina to read it again.</span>
